  "local_port": 46132,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My Windows 8.1 system is taking unusually long time to start / boot on Lenovo PC .Could there be any solutions?",
  "response": "If your Windows 8.1 system is taking a long time to boot on your Lenovo PC, there are several potential solutions you can try to improve the boot time:\n\n### 1. **Check Startup Programs**\n   - Press `Ctrl + Shift + Esc` to open Task Manager.\n   - Go to the **Startup** tab.\n   - Disable any unnecessary programs that you don't need to start with Windows. This can help speed up the boot process.\n\n### 2. **Use Disk Cleanup**\n   - Search for \"Disk Cleanup\" in the Start menu.\n   - Select the drive you want to clean (usually C:).\n   - Check options to clean \"Temporary files\" and \"System files.\"\n   - After cleaning, restart your system and see if it improves boot time.\n\n### 3. **Check for Malware**\n   - Run a full system scan using a trusted antivirus program to check for malware that may be slowing down your PC.\n\n### 4. **Update Drivers and Windows**\n   - Ensure all system drivers are up to date, especially chipset and storage drivers.\n   - Check for Windows updates by going to **Settings > Update and Recovery > Windows Update**.\n\n### 5. **Check Disk Health**\n   - Open Command Prompt as Administrator (search for \"cmd\", right-click, and choose \"Run as Administrator\").\n   - Type `chkdsk C: /f /r` and press Enter to check and fix disk errors. You may need to restart your computer to perform this.\n\n### 6. **Optimize and Defragment Hard Drive**\n   - Open \"This PC\", right-click on your C: drive, and select **Properties**.\n   - Go to the **Tools** tab and click on **Optimize** to run the defragmentation tool.\n\n### 7. **Adjust BIOS/UEFI Settings**\n   - Restart your PC and enter the BIOS/UEFI setup (usually by hitting a key like F2, DEL, or F10 during boot).\n   - Check for settings related to boot order, fast boot options, or secure boot. Sometimes changing certain settings can impact boot speed.\n\n### 8. **Check for Windows Updates**\n   - Go to **Settings > Update and Recovery > Windows Update** to ensure your system is up-to-date. Installing all available updates can improve performance.\n\n### 9. **Perform a System Restore**\n   - If the slow boot started recently, consider performing a System Restore to revert your system back to a previous point when it was working normally.\n\n### 10. **Check Hardware Issues**\n   - Test your hard drive health. Use a tool like CrystalDiskInfo to check if the hard drive is failing.\n   - If your system has an HDD, consider upgrading to an SSD for significantly faster loading times.\n\n### 11. **Reinstall Windows**\n   - As a last resort, if none of the above methods work and the problem persists, you may consider backing up your data and reinstalling Windows.\n\n### 12. **Contact Support**\n   - If you have warranty support or are unsure, contacting Lenovo support may provide you with specific solutions tailored for your PC model.\n\nBy following these suggestions, you should be able to improve the boot time of your Windows 8.1 system.",
